@{b}Words from MGN's Gadfly Artiste and Editroid
by Dave Matthews@{ub}

Do you remember the avant-guard film/music video "Koyaanisqatsi"? In one
scene, a man stands on a street corner, while everything around him is
speeding around on fast forward. That's what I feel like, these days. It's
been a mere few months since 60 and 66 MHz Pentiums have been available, and
they're already being phased out by Intels new 90 and 100 MHz Pentiums.
These new chips not only run faster, they run cooler and use less energy,
and should be less expensive overall to manufacture, for Intel and for Clone
makers. They also probably are the last nail in the coffin of the 680x0
chips by Motorola, whose chip market has pretty much been crushed by the
Intel Juggernaut.

Apple, Motorola and IBM are banking on the new PowerPC chip to provide an
alternative to Intel based computing. These PowerPC chips are "RISC",
(Reduced Instruction Set Computing) and have many advantages over the more
traditional processors like Intel's Pentium. In general, they offer more
horsepower at a better price. The PowerPC chip also offers addtional
goodies like built-in DSP (Digital Signal Processing), which the new Macs
can use for voice processing or even emulating a modem.

The only problem is a large one indeed. These new RISC chips are compatible
with NEITHER Intel's x86/Pentium line NOR Motorola's 680x0 line. Since you
can't sell even superior hardware without software, this poses a big hurdle
for Apple, Motorola and IBM to overcome. Their answer is "emulation", both
to run traditional Macintosh programs and to run PC compatible programs.

The problem with that is, basically, performance sucks. The new PowerPC Macs
can run most if not all Mac software, but not at anywhere near the level one
might expect from a 66-80 Mhz machine (The PowerPC's emulate a 68020). And
while they can also run most PC programs, it's even worse, with performance
matching low end '386 or even AT systems.

Not many PC people will be lured by "the world's fastest AT", when they can
have a 100 MHz 486 or 90 MHz Pentium for about the same price. Especially
now that most Macintosh software is also available on Windows.

While Intel and Motorola push the boundries of personal computer processors,
the industry, and computer users are faced with a far more serious problem.
The standard AT type architecture is laughably unable to cope with the
demands of todays modern software, much less tomorrows. To meet the needs
of a multimedia oriented society computers have to have great sound, great
graphics and animation, lots of bandwidth, and, MOST importantly, they have
to be easy to set up and use. Things like IRQ and DMA conflicts, 640k ram
limits, unending video and sound driver hassles just don't cut it.

Microsoft's "real-soon-now" Windows 4.0 is supposed to offer plug and play,
but even if it works, will offer very little to those who are not willing
to invest in hundreds of dollars worth of new type of cards, not to mention
the massive RAM and hard drive requirements.

Of course, the Amiga has solved many of these problems already, but sadly,
has pretty much been locked out of the mainstream. It remains to be seen if
these new PowerPC Macs (or the upcoming IBM PowerPCs) can unlock this puzzle.

--Dave
