@{b}The Rumors Among us...@{ub}

Note: These are just rumours, intended as entertainment, and should be 
taken as such.

By now most of you will have heard all the rumours flying around.
Apparently, CBM is virtually out of business. Their stock value has
dropped to pocket change, and they have almost no working capital. They
even stopped trade on their stock recently. They are in negotiations with
their creditors now.

Sony Amiga Makes it Possible? This is the most persistant rumour I've
seen. Sony is supposed to have bought out Commodore. Actually, this could
be quite good news. SONY has many interests which mesh quite nicely with
the Amiga. However, as I write this, no one has bought out CBM (at least
not yet).

Another rumor has it that CBM itself asked that its stock be withdrawn for
one day to scare its creditors into easing up.

Of course, Hewlett Packard is always good for some gossip. Apparently HP
DID buy a substantial amount of stock recently. They also recently inked a
technology sharing deal with Commodore concering the AGA chipset and HP's
plans for a TV Top Information Highway/Multimedia box. Commodore, of course,
has plans to use HP's PA (Precision Architecture) RISC chips future
machines.

The latest "takover of the week" has it that Phillips has bought CBM. While
this is doubtful, Phillips might actually be able to compete in the CDROM
Multimedia market if they did acquire the CD³² technology. On the other
hand, they might also kill the Amiga, so as to have one less competitor
making their CD-i look so lame.

One thing I do know is that the Engineers at Commodore are still hard at
work on AAA, and the next generation of Amigas. As you read this, the
A4000 tower systems are in the hands of developers, and Version 3.1 of
the Amiga OS is finished, and waiting for the documentation to be printed
in order to ship.

It's way too early to panic/rejoice over the latest wave of rumours. I
suppose, one way or another, we will all find out the truth over the next
few months. Until then, might as well be optimistic, eh?



@{b}Are We Having Paranoia Yet?@{ub}

AGE Entertainment Software is pleased to publicly announce today, the
impending release of their first game for the Commodore Amiga computer
platform, Paranoia.

Paranoia is a first-person, scrolling action adventure game which takes
elements from popular role playing games like Dungeon Master and Ultima
Underworld while maintaining action elements usually present in games
more like Alien Breed or Uridium and mixes it all together with elements
from popular science fiction films like Alien and Star Wars.

The player takes the place of a member of the crew from an interstellar
starship which is transporting cargo through the cosmos.  The ship is
attacked by an unknown alien race for no apparent reason, and the ship
is boarded by "Hoarders", creatures which roam the dark hallways of the
ship in search of human prey.  The player must find an escape off this
death trap in an adventure that will keep players on the edge of their
seat all the way through.  Obstacles must be overcome, and puzzles
solved in this epic story of a routine trip gone bad.

Combine all this action and adventure with a mixture of graphics rendered
with NewTek's amazing LightWave 3.0 and digitized clay animation and you
have an experience like nothing anyone has ever seen before on a personal
computer.

Should players succeed in this harrowing mission of mercy, they can
continue on in the story of this lonely crusader in Paranoia 2: Colony.
This story picks up where the first left off, with our hero landing his
escape vehicle on a nearby planet which harbours a colony filled with
mystery. Then, finally, comes the third and last game in the Paranoia
trilogy. Paranoia 3: Revenge goes to the home planet of the "Hoarders"
and takes our hero along for the ride.  Follow amazing plot twists and
unparalleled action sequences in an unprecedented game series.

