@{b}Marc and Dave's Excellent Adventure, Part One
Two Wild and SCSI Guys Install the Odd Hard Drive.
By Marc Hoffman and Dave Matthews
@{ub}
Recently, Marc Hoffman bought a "bare bones" Maxtor SCSI hard drive as
a second drive for his Amiga 3000. We both figured installing it would
be a breeze, after all, the Amiga 3000 has a built in SCSI support.

Our first challenge came when we had to decide which "device ID number"
to set the Maxtor to. The SCSI standard allows for up to seven devices to
be daisy-chained. Each one must have its own unique ID number, which you
set by changing a jumper. A jumper is usually a little block which inserts
over two pins. In the Maxtor's case, the jumper was labeled J602,
and pins 5 through 10 controlled the SCSI ID. The drive came configured
with an ID of 6. To change to an ID of 5, you would move the block
connecting pins 7 and 8 to pins 9 and 10.

@{b}Maxtor 7120s SCSI Hard Drive ID Chart@{ub}
+----------+------------+---------------+---------------+------------------+
| SCSI ID  |  Priority  | J602 Pins 5-6 | J602 Pins 7-8 | J602 Pins 9-10   |
|----------+------------+---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    0     |  Lowest    |      0        |       0       |         0        |
|----------+------------+---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    1     |            |      0        |       0       |      Jumper      |
|----------+            +---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    2     |            |      0        |    Jumper     |         0        |
|----------+            +---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    3     |            |      0        |    Jumper     |      Jumper      |
|----------+            +---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    4     |            |   Jumper      |       0       |         0        |
|----------+            +---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    5     |            |   Jumper      |       0       |      Jumper      |
|----------+            +---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    6     |            |   Jumper      |    Jumper     |         0        |
|----------+------------+---------------+---------------+------------------|
|    7     |  Highest   |   Jumper      |    Jumper     |      Jumper      |
+----------+------------+---------------+---------------+------------------+

The problem was, who knew what the Amiga's controller and internal hard
drive were set to. Well, we figured, we might luck out. So we opened the
case, and mounted the drive in the second floppy drive bay.
It fit beautifully,  as the floppy mounting brackets also fit
a standard 3.5" SCSI hard drive. Cool.

Of course it didn't work. After assembly, the Amiga failed to boot.
Well, luckily, Marc was able to locate his Amiga manual, and lo and
behold, the controller was set to 7, and the original drive was set to 6.
So we changed the Maxtor to device five and proceeded.
The easy part was over.

I knew that you had to "terminate" the last device in a SCSI chain with
a terminator resistor pack. But, where are these terminators, and what
do they look like? Who knows. Neither the Maxtor installation sheet nor
the Commodore manual bothered to label or describe the terminator.
Were we supposed to look for a little metal guy with a bad attitude? 
We tried booting up, and it seemed to work. But mysterious crashes,
failure to boot and other stange behaviour confirmed our suspicion that
the SCSI chain was not correctly terminated.

Well, a call to Computability (where Marc purchased the drive) finally
cleared this up. Terminator are flat rectangular black or sometimes
yellow components with a row of pins. Jeez, what's the big secret?

Click here to see SCSI Terminators-->@{"SCSI Terminators" system "display.s SCSIPIC.IFF"}

Anyway, after removing both hard drives, we found and removed the
original Quantum drive's terminator packs, leaving the Maxtor's in
place. Success at last. A quick trip to Commodore's HDToolbox to
partition and format the drive, and we were set.

Whew! It's amazing what a little knowledge can do. I don't know why
nobody has seen fit to actually label or describe a SCSI terminator,
but it sure would have saved us some aggravation and time.
Well, you heard it here first.



@{b}
Marc and Dave's Excellent Adventure, Part Two
Hangin' with the ROMboys (2.04, that is)
By Marc Hoffman and Dave Matthews
@{ub}
When last we left our intrepid heroes, Dave and Marc, they had
successfully installed a second SCSI hard drive in Marc's A3000. Or...
so they thought...(Cue the creepy music.)

It turns out that things were not to be that simple. Some of the time,
Marc's Amiga would boot fine, other times it would boot but refuse to
recognize the new hard drive. And worse, occasionally it would not boot
from the hard drive at all, requiring a floppy. There are few things
less appealing than seeing a prompt asking you to insert volume System,
when volume System is a hard drive!

Moreover, HDToolbox kept changing the SCSI ID numbers of the Maxtor!
Sometimes it would report as 5, sometimes as 3. Of course, no one
we talked to could explain what was going on, and in fact, I don't
think the tech guys really even believed us.

Well, following the recommendation of several tech dudes, Marc decided
to upgrade to 2.04, at which time we would install the ROMs, change the
SCSI jumpers, and generally get things working. So Marc ordered his
upgrade from Grapevine, and waited...and waited...and waited.

Finally, after an agravating month, the package arrived. Gathering our
fortitude, we sat down to install the ROMs. I'd like to gloat over how
easy it was to do the upgrade, but I'd be lying like a cheap rug. It was
actually sort of a pain.

The A3000, as you may know, comes in one of those dainty little compact
type of cases. Hey, it looks nice, but talk about cramped quarters! My
friend, Don, the PC guy, used to have a Gateway '386sx in the same
slimline type of case, and working with it was the same rare pleasure.

And of course, where are these ROM sockets? Since ROMs will probably be
replaced more often than say, a surface mounted CPU, Commodore surely
would make the sockets accessible, right? Har. To get at the ROM sockets
requires dissasembling almost the entire computer, including removing
the floppy drive, hard drive and power supply subassembly. Jeeez, CBM,
were you afraid the ROM snatcher's would steal your ROMs while you
slept? Sigh.

Inserting the actual ROM chips was pretty easy. But putting the beast
back together, especially the really fun part where you get to thread
a bunch of cables through a 1/2" crawl space while at the same
time lowering a 20lb drive assembly into place, well, let's just say
"this, I don't need."

As hardware goes, I'm not very impressed. Now, onto the software. Hey!
This is easy...maybe too easy! Actually, Commodore did an excellent job
with their installer program, something a lot of PC people could learn
from.

Ok, now Marc has a beautiful 2.04 machine. The bad news is, the drive is
still acting funky. Now, although the 3000 boots up fine every time, she
won't recognize the second hard drive, until you do a warm boot. Then it
comes up just fine. Hmmmm. Oh well, tune in again, same bat time, same
bat station...



@{b}
Marc and Dave's Excellent Adventure, Part Three
68040 and Goal to Go
By Marc Hoffman and Dave Matthews
@{ub}
Once more unto the Breach! After installing both a second SCSI hard
drive, and 2.04 ROM's in Marc's long suffering A3000, you would think
we would leave well enough alone. But, you would be wrong!

Because Marc is primarily interested in 3D Graphics, he found his stock
16 MHz 68030 to be increasingly untenable. Then when he saw the Creative
Computer ad for Progressive Peripheral Inc's 25 MHz 68040 board for about
$500, his destiny was clear.

After receiving the board from Creative, we set out to install the board,
and also hopefully correct the odd boot problem with his SCSI drive setup.
We even planned to document the whole process with a Polaroid.

How did it go? (Drum roll please)...Not well, folks. Right off the bat,
the disk with the 68040 libraries and utilities was bad. Not just a
read/write error here or there either. This disk was blown seven ways
from Sunday.

GRRRRRRONNNNNNKKK!!! Man, how I hate that sound! Dead in the water
before we even got the hardware out of the box.

I whipped out Dave Haynie's Disk Salv program, but unfortunately, all
the main files were totally corrupted, beyond all mortal help. Perhaps
an excorsism is in order? Actually, speaking of excorsism, in the
June 15, 1993 issue of PC Magazine there is a cartoon by Richard Tennant
that sums up our experience on this A3000 perfectly. Go see it, it's
hilarious.

Worse, this is all happening on Saturday, and McCook is way out in the
boon docks, and Marc lives about 150 miles away, which is a long drive
for nothing. Well, maybe we can get the file from PPI's BBS. Since
I don't have a modem for my Amiga (and that's another sad story), I fired
up the trusty C128, which never lets me down. Alas, Progressive has
progressed beyond their old BBS phone number; they have either changed
the number, or simply abandoned it. We tried a few other BBS's but not
surprisingly, none had any Vendor areas, and most weren't too keen on
unregistered dweebs like us downloading files anyway. We also called
a number of actual human types. While there are a surprising amount of
dealers open on Saturday, most of the technical support people are
long gone. So, after a few hours of futile calls, and head scratching,
our shoulders slump in defeat. One friendly soul suggested we contact
the McCook Commodore User Group for help. Sigh.

Marc finally got through to a tech support person from Creative, who
promised to send a replacement disk right out, so I guess we will try
again in a week or so.

This whole boondoggle took so long, we didn't get to try changing the
SCSI ID jumpers to correct the weird boot up snag Marc's A3000 still has.
So Marc packed up his A3000, his virgin 68040 board, and his unused
Polaroid camera and headed back to Julesburg. Oh well, stay tuned for
another exciting episode of Dave and Marc's Adventures in Upgrade City



@{b}
Marc and Dave's Excellent Adventure, Part Four
The Road Goes on Forever
Installing Progressive's 68040
By Marc Hoffman and Dave Matthews
@{ub}
It's a good thing Kirk, Spock and Scotty didn't have to deal with late
twentieth century technology--the Klingons would have won every time!

As reported last time, Marc Hoffman bought a Progressive Peripherals
25 MHz 68040 accelerator board for his 16 MHz Amiga 3000. Unfortunately,
when it arrived, the setup disk was corrupted, and thus we could not
install the board. Marc called Creative Computers (where he bought
the board), and they promised to send a replacement right out.

They told Marc they had shipped it Federal Express, Tuesday, June 1,
yet it took about two weeks to arrive from California to Colorado. 

Before we installed the '040, we changed the drive SCSI ID numbers as
follows: Quantum boot drive,ID 0, Maxtor second drive, ID 1. This is
recommended procedure for IBM SCSI installations, but it didn't help.
To access the Maxtor, we still need to warm boot right after powering up.
A bad omen of things to come.

Well, Marc installed the software onto his hard drive. And then we
proceeded to the hardware (at last). We unplugged everything, removed
the case, the daughterboard and the drivebay subassembly, revealing
the motherboard. Following the manual, we pried (carefully) a certain
RAM chip out and inserted Progressive's Static RAM chip in it's place.
We then changed three jumpers, J100, J104 and J851.

Oddly, Progressive's manual had the position of the Jumper J102
differently from Marc's motherboard, but since it didn't say anything
about changing it, we left it alone.

Inserting the actual 68040 board was easy. It fits quite nicely in the
allotted space. We then connected the floppy power connector to the
'040 board to power the fan, which involved switching the floppy drive
and Maxtor HD, because the floppy power cable was too short. We then
reassembled everything.

Upon trying to reboot, however, the Amiga choked on the startup
sequence line containing the 68040Init command. Apparently, the
installation program put extraneous quotes around the command, sigh.
After fixing that, the Amiga booted up fine (except for the weird hard
drive thing). Well, we played around for awhile, and then Marc tried
Imagine. CRASH. We Rebooted and tried Wing Commander CRASH. CRASH CRASH
CRASH. No matter what we tried, or how we set the '040 options
(copyback mode on/off etc), it would no longer run for more than a few
minutes.

The Progressive manual warned of this condition, apparently a problem
with a certain DMAC chip (whatever that is). Apparently it overheats on
some 3000s. Progressive states that this is a random problem with early
A3000s. A call to a nearby Amiga dealer tech guy gave us a different
story--according to him, this is a random problem with some A3000s, and
it only bothers Progressive boards. Creative Computers tech guy, however,
stated that all A3000s have DMAC chips that overheat with an '040, and
you need a special DMAC­040 to run ANY '040 board. At least they all
agree that there is a DMAC in the A3000. SIGH.

Worse than that, now we can't even get a divorce! Once we removed the
68040, and reset all jumpers, the 3000 refused to boot, even from a
floppy. Talk about your shotgun weddings!

Finally, Marc reinstalled the board, and it seemed to work. Apparently,
Imagine cannot run with the COPYBACK cache on, and worse, once Imagine
crashed, it took a COLD BOOT (completely turning off the machine) before
the problem was cleared up. At first it appeared most of Marc's problems
were solved. BUT then the hard drives started acting up again, the HD
program kept changing the SCSI ID numbers, requiring resetting the
drives. And before long the 68040 starting crashing again.

My recommendation? Don't buy Progressive's Board unless:

 1> you are a trained technician or
 2> you have a trained technician whom you trust put it in and test it
    (preferably with a few hours of burn in), and one who guarantees
    their work.

Had Progressive included some diagnostic software, we would have stood
a better chance of determining if it was running correctly.
 
At this time, Marc has given in and taken his Amiga to a not so local
dealer (who of course, has his own different opinion as to why Marc's
A3000 is acting up. Nor did he believe Marc's hard drive problem).

As of July 15, more than a month after Marc bought the board, the dealer
has determined Marc's A3000 has a bad motherboard, and is still waiting
for Commodore to ship out a replacement. Apparently the SCSI problem was
a symptom of a flakey board, and the 68040 finally pushed the motherboard
over the edge. Marc also ordered the special 040 version of the DMAC
chip. Hopefully, he will have his computer sometime this century.

I admit I'm no computer engineer, hardware hacker or seasoned service
tech, but I've put (successfully) a lot of hardware in a lot of
computers, Amiga, PC etc, and this just is not right.

If the A3000 had a flaky motherboard, that is one thing. But why was it
so hard to get a straight answer about Progressive's '040 board?
Progressive (if they are still out there somewhere--are they still out
there somewhere?) needs to rethink their product, particularly the
support documentation and programs. A diagnostic program would have
helped quite a bit. Perhaps this explains the cheap price?

And what about that DMAC chip thing? We heard from four or five
presumably competent tech people, and they all told us completely
different stories. What's the deal? Well, kids, tune in again next month,
for the thrilling conclusion (we hope) to Marc and Dave's Bogus Journey!



@{b}
Marc and Dave's Excellent Adventure, Part Five
A Case Study in Futility, or Marc's Tempestuous
Summer Romance with the 68040
By Marc Hoffman and Dave Matthews
@{ub}
"Nothing Works, and Nobody Cares" - Woody Allen

WARNING! DON'T BUY A 68040 board from Progressive Peripherals Inc (PPI),
before you read this! As some of you may know, Progressive recently has
had a string of bad luck, including a fire which destroyed their
headquarters, all of which has resulted in Progressive's (at least the 
Amiga related stuff) demise.

From personal experience, and talking to dealers and repair personnel,
Progressive had a major quality assurance problem with their 68040 boards.

These boards are often advertised at Blow-Out prices, but before you buy,
better check the fine print: can you get a refund if it doesn't work?

Over the past four Months, MGN has reported on Marc Hoffman's struggles
with PPI's 040 board. I'll recap those struggles, then bring you
"the rest of the story".

Just the Facts: Late spring, 1993, Marc buys a Progressive Peripheral
Inc (PPI) 040 25 MHz accelerator board from Creative Computers.
It arrives, but the accompanying disk with the required 68040 libraries
and files was trashed, so he called Creative Computers and asked for a
replacement disk. TWO weeks and several phone calls later, he finally
received the disk.

We installed the board, carefully following the manual, but after
numerous unexplained crashes, and erratic behaviour, it appeared the
board simply was not going to work. A dozen or so phone calls resulted
in a variety of theories and advice, none of which helped.
And Progressive's tech support was nowhere to be found.

Finally, we decided to give up and took the board out. Now Marc's
A3000 wouldn't boot at all, no startup screen, no hard drive activity
light, no nothing. After further panicky efforts, it appeared
professional help was needed.

Marc took his computer to the Computer Room, in Aurora, CO, with the
upshot being $600 out of Marc's pocket for a new motherboard, and of
course, the 30 day return period for the 040 board had passed
(and Progressive was not answering their phones). Creative Computers
agreed to trade Marc's '040 board for a Mercury 040. Marc didn't really
want another PPI product, but GVP has apparently stopped production on
their A3000 GForce 040 products. So Marc shelled out ANOTHER $400 for
the 28 MHz Mercury 040. 

Guess what? Surprise! It doesn't work! Surprise! Creative won't refund
Marc's Money. Reason? Quote- "There are just some things we won't
refund your money on." Unquote. After numerous increasingly irate phone
calls, Marc received a refund on the original 040, and credit for the
difference he paid for the Mercury, which he spent on a GVP EGS Spectrum
24 Bit graphics board.

Those are facts to date. In my humble opinion, this whole thing was
nothing short of a criminal joke. Progressive handled their business
very poorly, leaving customers in the lurch, Creative Computers fawned
off merchandise they knew bloody well was troublesome, from a company
that was out of business,  without so much as a casual warning, and then
had the gall to refuse a refund. And 1 1/2 thumbs down to GVP for
dumping the A3000 owners in favor of the more "politically correct"
Video Toaster crowd. 

As for Marc, he is thinking about a A4000. You can bet he won't buy it
from Creative!



@{b}Film at Eleven Department:@{ub}
Marc just informed me that his A3000, with the newly refurbished mother-
board, has trashed his Maxtor Drive,or at least the data thereon. After
crashing severely, Marc found his 3000 wouldn't boot at all. Eventually,
it did, but wouldn't recognize the Maxtor drive at all. After going into
HDToolbox, Marc found his Maxtor listed, but it reported a Block size
mistmatch when he attempted to add the drive back to the device list.
Marc called the service tech at Computer Room in Aurora, but it didin't
look good for recovering the data. Marc even called a couple of Hard
Drive recovery places, (if you want to rake in the big moola, get into
this line of work!)

Anyway, as a last ditch effort to determine if the drive itself was
screwed up, Marc removed his orgiginal 50 MB SCSI drive and hooked up
the Maxtor in its place. Amazingly, it actually worked. Apparently the
motherboard is at fault. This is good news for the data stored on the
Maxtor, but it appears the 3000 is in critical condition. It looks like
time for either a new computer, or at least a new motherboard. Stay tuned
for MARC'S MOMENTOUS UPGRADE.
