@NODE OPINION "Ed Becerra's Page"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}Computers, Privacy & Civil Disobedience.
Opinion by Ed Becerra@{ub}

First, a statement of the problem, folks.  Then, what computers 
have to do with it & what it has to do with us, O.K.?

There's been a lot of talk about privacy in the information age, 
especially from human leftovers & relics from the '60's.  
Granted, they can be annoying, particularly when they holler 
about freedom & all you're interested in is keeping yourself & 
your family safe in an increasingly UN-safe world.  In streets 
full of Russian surplus AK-47's, crack, Uzi's, ice, Saturday 
Night specials, cat, 9mm pistols, crystal meth, and other such 
things, the common man is far too terrified to worry about issues 
that seem far away & unimportant.  What HE'S (or SHE'S) worried 
about is how to avoid being cut down in a drive-by shooting, or 
getting whacked by a disgruntled employee who returns to work 
with an M-16 & a bag full of ammo.  He/She wants to keep their 
kids off drugs, & in a school that is reasonably safe, a school 
where they don't have to worry about their little darling getting 
caught in the crossfire between the Crips & the Bloods shooting 
it out over who has the rights to sell drugs in that particular 
playground.

There's nothing wrong with their fear.  It's a very real 
occurrence in the world today & something that we have to deal 
with.  But there's another danger that most people don't seem to 
be noticing.  And that's the danger of trading your freedom for 
safety.  Allowing the government to rule every aspect of your 
life in return for a guarantee that you don't have to worry about 
anything anymore, because Big Brother will take care of all your 
problems FOR you.

Well, if that's what they want, that's up to them.  But kindly 
leave the rest of us ALONE, Thank you very much!  If you're so 
terrified of freedom & life in general that you want to a safe 
slave rather that a free man whose life is always in danger, 
please, go ahead!  (And let's make no mistake here, folks.  If 
you're a free man, taking care of yourself, danger large & small 
will always be out there, waiting.)

Just don't drag the rest of us with you, O.K.?

So, enough with the soapbox....

What do our computers have to do with the problem?  Well, aside 
from the I.R.S. and the covert intelligence community, (Can you 
say C.I.A., children?  Good, I knew you could.), the largest user 
of computers in the U.S.A. is the DMV.  Yeah, that's right, the 
Department of Motor Vehicles. All 50+ of them.

Just recently, an article in WIRED magazine pointed out that if 
you have an over-due library book in Wisconsin, you can LOSE your 
driver's license here in Colorado or Nebraska.  How?  Here's how 
it works....

A great many communities, and for that matter, whole states, are 
trying to solve their legal problems with people's driving 
permits.  We seem to have forgotten that the right to drive a car 
ISN'T a right after all.  And unlike passing a new law, which 
requires the approval of the voting public, the loss of your 
driving permit for any of a number of reasons is merely a matter 
of writing up a new regulation.  An example of this is 
Wisconsin's little stunt.  In this state, failure to pay any 
state or city fine will result in the loss of your license.  Any 
fine!  Get ticketed for failure to shovel your sidewalk, for 
over-due library books, junk in the front yard, anything like 
that & you lose your license.  If, that is, you should fail (or 
refuse) to pay your fine.  Wow.  And since other states cross co-
operate, Nebraska, say, will pull your Nebraskan license at 
Wisconsin's request.

Works with Kentucky, too.  The great state of Kentucky is using 
this little trick to keep kids in school & off drugs.  How?  
Let's see.  Follow me, children.  Under Kentucky's "high school 
drop-out law" of 1990, students who drop out, have nine or more 
unexcused absences, or who become "academically deficient" 
(failing to pass at least four of their classes, say) lose the 
right to drive unless they can prove that family hardship on 
their part REQUIRES them to drive.

In Oregon, any child convicted of drinking, drug possession, or 
caught with a firearm in any public building loses his/her 
license until the age of 17.  After 17, if caught again, they 
lose it again, until their 18th birthday.  Interestingly enough, 
of the 109 different offenses that can lose you your license, 
only 27 of them are traffic related.

The driver's license has become something it was never intended 
to be: A badge of good citizenship.  Pay your bills to city and 
state, pay your child support, don't get caught using drugs, stay 
away from those nasty old firearms, and the state will let you 
keep on trucking.

And all of this was made possible by the rapid transfer, sorting, 
and cross-referencing of information that can only be done by 
computers.  If the various DMV's suddenly lost their computers, 
(or the IRS, the FBI, the CIA, NSA, or the Financial Crimes 
Enforcement Network a.k.a. FinCEN, or any of a number of the 
alphabet soup gang living in Washington, D.C.), they'd be as 
helpless as a blind, deaf, quadriplegic, coma patient in a 
hospital straight-jacket.  Something that a lot of us would wish 
on the IRS, at least.

And there is one solution to this problem that will occur to 
every teen-age hacker & cyberpunk out there.  An ugly solution.  
Viruses.  Like I said.  Ugly.  After all, we're supposed to be
* RESPONSIBLE ADULTS * here.  Yeah, right.  Yet, if the legal, 
political methods fail us and Big Brother wins the right to spy 
on us & control our lives all by using a combination of computer 
power & loopholes in the law, what then?  No matter HOW much we 
despise the socially irresponsible vandals who write these 
destructive little programs, we may end up needing their help!  
Thoreu recommended civil disobedience towards an unjust 
government.  Well, viruses, logic bombs, trojan horses, and worms 
look like they'll become the new weapons for those who oppose a 
government, for whatever reasons.

And effective weapons they'll be.  Robert T. Morris, with a worm 
less than 48 kilobytes in size, managed to disable some 2000 
computers on the Internet.  The scary part is, he intended it as 
a joke.  He meant to do no serious damage.  Think of what he, or 
anyone else, could have done if they had malicious intentions.  
Nasty.

I really HATE the thought that someday I might find myself on the 
same side as these vandalistic idiots, but politics can make for 
strange bedfellows.  And should we need this sort of weapon 
against the government, we'll need it desperately.

Better buy all the anti-virus protection you can, folks.  And 
back up your data as often as you can.  Daily, if possible.  Life 
on the nets is about to get a lot more complicated.  And for some 
of us, dangerous.

Bye for now, folks. See you next month.  Sleep easy.  It's 
probably your last chance to.  Hee, hee, hee.
@ENDNODE




@NODE USERPORT "Loadstar Disk Magazine for the C64"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}Loadstar 64 #118
Softdisk Publishing
PO Box 30008
Shreveport, LA 71130-0008
1-800-831-2694
3 Months: $29.95
6 Months: $49.95
12 Months: $89.95
24 Months:$149.95

Review by Dave Matthews@{ub}

Sometimes the little things can make the biggest difference. One of the
reasons I like Loadstar is their constant attention to details, and the
fact they're always trying to improve.

One of those improvements is offering their product on both the 1541 and
the newer 3.5" 1581 disk format. Loadstar is the only company I know of
that took the effort and expense to support the 1581 format directly. I
don't know how many 64 and 128 users own a 3.5" drive (either the 1581 or
CMD's new FD-2000 or FD-4000 series), but it's a major step, and once again
shows Loadstars committment to the 64 and 128. Of course, Loadstar still
supports the 1541, and those owners don't get cheated, even though the 1581
has much more storage space than the four sides of a 1541 disk. All the
`meat and potatoes', programs and documentation etc, that are on the 1581
are on the 1541 disks. On the other hand, the 1581 issues usually contain
some filler material, extra source code, stories, subscriber's Forum.

Loadstar 118, my first 1581 format issue, starts off with Fender Tucker's
essay on inspiration. Fender's articles and essays and soliloquies are
always worthwhile reading, and elevate Loadstar from just another disk of
the month to a real magazine.

Jeff Jones' Soapbox provides the streetwise attitude to Fender's off the
wall wisdom. In issue 118, he takes a hard look at PC's, and what they're
coming too.

Zero Page is a column devoted to learning the 64, inside and out. Usually,
it's divided into three articles, BASICS, which cover neophyte level stuff,
BYTES, topics for the advanced dudes and dudettes, and BITs, which, not
surprising is for the hackers out there. This issue, BASICS has a list of
Commodore specific books put together by Don Craig, BYTES covers converting
those pesky Print Shop graphics from IBM to Commodore, and BITS, as is
appropriate for MGN's hard ware issue, is Fender's hardware hack for getting
rif of those annoying printer interface wires which connect to your
cassette port, and (when not busy getting all tangled up) provide power to
interface.

In the ever popular Brainware section, first up is a quiz on Hieroglyphics,
those intriguing Egyption inscriptions, done by Rick Hephart. Letter Drop
is Robert Markland's computer version of these popular pen and paper
puzzles, and Letter Drop Maker, also by Robert Markland, is a little program
to create said puzzles for your long suffering friends to solve. Barbara
Schulak serves up the usual Puzzle Page, with a cinematic theme. Now, I'm
not much of a puzzle fiend, really, but even if you don't like puzzles, be
sure and read the intro text, written by that Scourge of Banality, Fender
Tucker. Final, Barbara Schulak winds up the BrainWare section with Movie
Gram 118.

Moving right along, in the FunWare section, Tony Patenaude creates some
new and devious mazes for Jon Mattson's scrolling maze game. Jon Mattson
also presents Maze Chase Maker, which, not surprisingly, lets you create
your own mazes for this game.

If you're tired of the average flight simulator, how about taking the
place of an air traffic controller? Airport '94, by Dave Moorman,
puts you in the control tower.

HelpWare has Loadstar Catalog, by Jeff Jones. This database of Loadstar
issues let's you quickly search through back issues.

Steve Emsley's series of game (helpers | cheaters) continues in this
issue with patches for Chomp!, Cyberworld and Double Dragon II amongst
others.

Also in helpware is another of those amazing Euro Demos, Chaos 101
provides a brief education on fractals and Demo making philosophy of
Elwix, the creator of this demo.

Stereo is the theme of this months MusicWare. Mark Dickenson's
StereoPlayer 10.3 has numerous features for maximizing your 64's
SID music Prowes, including support for StereoSID songs. These are
six voice songs, created for the SID Symphony cartridge, which adds
another SID chip (and thus six voices) to your 64. I believe CMD still
sells these.

To go along with the player, of course, are a pile of stereo songs, by
Dave Marquis and Diane Bryan. Even if you don't have the Stereo
Cartridge, these still sound amazingly good.

In the GrafixWare section are another horde of those pesky Print Shop
images, this time in a naval theme. Greg Scheidler presents a program
for printing up to 100 of the little images, on Epson or SG printers.

Finally, Jan Logsdon and Charles Hogarth present some GEOPaint clip art
of playing children.

@ENDNODE



@NODE CONFUSION "Amazing confusion for the PC Compatible"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}Hasta La Vista, Baby
How I removed Stacker from my PC and Lived to Tell the Tale
by T.J. Maddock
@{ub}
Stacker is a popular "on-the-fly" file compression package. While it does
what is says, it also creats enough problems that I decided to remove it.
For any brave Stacker owner who wishes to remove Stacker from his or her
system, my first recommendation is to find someone to buy your Stacked
PC (hopefully not someone you intend to keep as a friend!), and then just
buy a new computer. Seriously, after you add stacker to your system, it's
pretty much "till death do us part."

I read four or five reviews of Stacker before the purchase, and not one ever
mentioned all the hassles Stacker will cause you. It doesn't like QEMM and
other disk and memory optimizers, it made my hard drive rather unreliable,
it uses up precious memory, and it makes upgrading really difficult.

The Stacker manual has lots of info on setting up Stacker, but very little
on removing it. I don't have the emotional fortitude to detail every
tedious step but here is an overview of removing stacker. I had Stacked
the Original C: boot drive, resulting in a compressed C: partition, and an
uncompressed D: partition.

First, I backed up all my files, programs and data. Second I made a floppy
system disk in case anything went wrong (it did). I somehow lost a whole
directory of TrueType Fonts. They just disappeared. Picture a grown man
having a temper tamtrum in front of his computer.

Next I Used SREMOVE to kill the stacked drive. My Stacked C: drive was now
history. My D: drive (under Stacker) is now C: (sigh). It had enough files
to boot, but all my other programs and data were gone, except for the
backups I made to floppy disk. I edited the autoexec.bat files to remove
all references to Stacker, and rebooted, and crashed, and edited some more
and rebooted, and again until I got it right. There's several references
to Stacker in the autoexec.bat and config.sys files which must be deleted
(carefully).

Finally I got my PC back, and I copied all the files back to drive C:.
Then, I had to re-optimize everything with QEMM, which is actually MUCH
easier without Stacker.

Stacker is almost worthwhile (missed it by that much!), but it just made
my PC too jerry-rigged and fragile for my tastes, and now, just when I
get everything back to normal, Chairman Bill wants me to use upgrade to
DOS 6.0 with DoubleSpace? Yeah, right.

P.S. I hear Stac Electronics won their little ($120 million) lawsuit against
Microsoft. I guess this means no more double space. I never thought I'd be
saying this, but thank you Stac! On second thought, even though Stac won,
I'm sure no good can come of mixing computer weasels and lawyer weasels.
So...never mind!
